nonlinear: {
  shape: rectangle
  style: {
    fill: "#2a1a3a"
    stroke: "#7b2d8b"
    stroke-width: 3
    border-radius: 8
    font-color: "#da70d6"
    font-size: 12
  }
  label: |md
    **Why Ch is Nonlinear over GF(2)**
    A linear function satisfies: f(a ⊕ b) = f(a) ⊕ f(b)
    Ch contains AND(x, y) — multiplication in GF(2).
    Multiplications produce cross-terms (e.g., xy) that cannot
    be expressed as any linear combination ax ⊕ by ⊕ cz.
    Proof sketch:
      Ch(1,0,0) = 0,  Ch(0,1,0) = 0
      Ch(1⊕0, 0⊕1, 0) = Ch(1,1,0) = 1
      But  Ch(1,0,0) ⊕ Ch(0,1,0) = 0 ⊕ 0 = 0 ≠ 1
    → XOR-linearity fails → Ch is **nonlinear** ✓
  |
}
title -> formula
formula -> table_header
table_header -> r0
r0 -> r1
r1 -> r2
r2 -> r3
r3 -> r4
r4 -> r5
r5 -> r6
r6 -> r7
r7 -> legend_x0
r7 -> legend_x1
legend_x0 -> nonlinear
legend_x1 -> nonlinear